social_posts.post_text:
This last year has been all about them (and a little about my guy in the reflection - what a symbolic image). 

In 2022 I took time to honor my motherhood. I slowed down. Created boundaries with a self guided maternity leave from wedding work. I absorbed hours of snuggles. I made peace with nights that were endless and turned to morning. I gave up my body to nourish another every single day. I read a myriad of parenting books to heal myself and be a better human for them. I simply dealt with my present instead of hyper focusing on the future. It’s what all three of us needed. It was quite a difficult and evolutionary year. 

2022 was also the last of my 30s. I am reflecting deeply on the decade and how it’s been largely dedicated to home, stability, and foundation building. I began those years getting married. I have now ended them a mother of two, feeling complete with those choices. I self sacrificed (without regret) a lot of my creative passions and art career/academic/exhibition goals. 

The next decade will not be the same. I can feel it. I’m all around life and self engaged. There is much to be created and with new confidence, one I haven’t felt since my 20s (however, back then the feeling was hollow - now it is layered, profound, engaged, and proud).

Happy New Year, friends. Cheers to you and deeper self discovery.

📸: Ashley (of course), @ash_e_l

(And sorry for the repost if you follow me personally)

Happy Day, friends. I hope your expressions of love are soft and powerfully feminine, your gifts slightly surreal, and your soul transparent. May you be alive and weathered and textured  today, for yourself and those you care for.

Week One back in the studio. 
Prepped multiple mediums and surfaces. Had one of my dearest friends (@elysehradecky) come to talk to my class about all things modern apprenticeship and how it affects personal work (as she prepares for an upcoming solo exhibition). She stayed till Sunday to: have a gorgeous studio painting day together, spend copious amounts of time with my two boys, talked philosophy/art/life/politics/PhD aspirations/higher Ed/etc, listened to our husbands record and play music together, pull needed and telling tarot/oracle cards, and simply “be” together as 6 lovely (one cranky and teething) humans under one roof. What a perfect start to this next creative chapter. ♥️

Last night, just before 9pm, I turned 40. 

My husband and I are symbolically tied to the number 10. It’s not only part of our birthdays and anniversary but also tied to our children’s births. So new decades are felt deeper than they would otherwise. 

My 30s have been wonderful but in a different way than I thought. I imagined them filled with career accolades, teaching professionally, and an exhibition career that’d fill my CV with glowing pride. Instead, it grew into a decade of “home”“stability” “structure” “blueprints” “foundations” and “family”. 

At newly 30 I graduated with my masters. I got married. I started a creative admin job at UPenn, where I’d remain for 4 solid years (with a position change and promotion within 6months). At 32 I had my second solo within two years and was exhibiting non stop, but burnout made me unhappy and devastatingly untied to the subject matter. My suffocating paintings were doing just that. At 34 I got my first teaching job at PAFA. The same exact week of the semester starting, I learned I was pregnant with my beautiful son Lucian. At 35 I had him and developed some rough postpartum anxiety. That has been a battle that works through me like a rollercoaster still. That same year I quit my toxic 9-5 and poured myself into my business @irisandecho. Within 1 year it matched my admin salary and I was able to work and mother as I wanted. At 37 I decided to take my painting and teaching career to another level, add a day of daycare, get serious about my big commission I’d received, and change course. But the pandemic hit and closed everything down within DAYS of my birthday. My business was in limbo. I didn’t get the teaching job I was told I was perfect for. On a professional level, I was in a dark depth I cannot even describe. 

Lucian was a light during this time. Home life, teaching online, photo editing, and mothering full time was HARD… but age 3 was MAGIC. Another child was desired. A few days after turning 38 I learned I was pregnant with Oscar. 

Starting around when the fog of the first year of babyhood began clearing, 40 has been on the horizon and felt different. 

This next decade is for me. (More in caption).

Week Two. 
Cleaned and prepped my palette after nearly half a year of (unwanted) abandonment. Started three tondos. A little @pafacademy and @darlajacksonsculpture love on my Thursdays. Enjoyed a solid hour of @archenemyarts’ First Friday exhibitions before my kids proved bedtime is a real thing that needs to be strictly enforced. 😂 Finally spent time with one of my best friends (in person! - @alexgarantart), celebrating her solo at Arch and enjoying a chaos hang at the Franklin Institute with our crews. Then… 40. ♥️ Week three is already in progress and SOLID.

I started her as an experiment; to test all the research I’ve been doing over the last few years. She ended up blooming exactly as I desired and so… the first piece for my upcoming show is complete.

5 year olds aren’t easy but their hearts are pure, authentically curious, above and beyond creative, wildly hilarious, gems. 

My sweet Lucian has been collecting flowers for me since they began blooming. He picks them at recess and holds them tight till he sees me at the bus stop (did you know dandelions can stain palms?), he saves some and stores then in his lunchbox for me, he picks them on our walk home or from the backyard. 

After the first few, I asked him… “can I paint it?” The JOY on his face. 

And so here is the last three days worth. 

This cycle of growth, each year around his birthday, keeps this inspiration so deeply entrenched in my being. I am grateful.

I look forward to a painterly summer of lovingly plucked blooms; canvases to keep for myself.

Dear Artist Mother (in the trenches),

You are still there. It may have been 3 months, a year, or more since you’ve touched what was once so important to you… but that doesn’t mean it isn’t still who you are. You may be in a chrysalis.

PLEASE dont look around you and think you’re failing when you see others doing what you want to. Dont look at the parent with the child in the wrap, still painting without missing a beat, and compare. I did at first. It isn’t helpful. Dismiss the highlight reel.

Your journey is yours and yours alone. Some humans need pause. Some artists need more time than others. Some artists have quick momentary processes while others have slow methodical ones. Often your child and your creative needs will not be symbiotic. If you’re in a state of pause, you are, more than likely, in a cocoon and I encourage you to breathe and allow the change. Observe. Be still. Take new information in. Mother hard.

You are still an artist. You are still creating.

My own mothering adventure, just one week shy of SIX YEARS, has been a joyful, chaotic, heart wrenching, stunning, visceral, breaking, otherworldly experience. Plowing through would’ve been a disservice to my creative self and my, now, TWO beautiful sons. 

It wasn’t until this past February that Ive been able to put paint to canvas in a serious manner… since 2017. For six years I documented, wrote, cried, laughed, danced, tickled, screamed, watched, read, grew, planted, and FELT. 

Im just at the beginning of this creative shift. And my favorite part about this next chapter is the complete absence I feel for outside validation. I could take all of these paintings back home with me when my show is done and proudly display them on my wall for eternity. I will continue to feel confident it was the direction I needed to go, the right subject matter to say what I needed to say about who I’ve become these last six years, and get ready to make the next without worry. My pause was genuine, internal, growth.

So, please allow yourself to transform no matter what that looks like. You may feel lost but its possible you truly are just in a chrysalis.

You are still an artist.

Why is age 41 the limit of “emerging”?

After nearly seven years of pregnancy -> birth -> losing and finding myself in the first mind bending two years of childhood-> global pandemic -> second pregnancy -> losing and refinding myself AGAIN (all while trying to WORK and pay bills)… I am FINALLY EMERGING. 

I am making the best work (this show and planned beyond) I’ve ever made. It’s more skillful, more interesting, more intimate, more soulful, more MEANINGFUL than anything I could’ve even imagined in my 30s while I was racing against a biological clock to physically, mentally, and emotionally create the family I desired with my partner. 

So why am I battling against grants, I finally feel ready to apply to, because I’m at their age limit for “emerging artist”?! I am JUST STARTING at 40.

How the art world fails mothers time and time again will never cease to amaze me. How deeply entrenched in the patriarchy it is, will never seem to stop surprising me. It is so entrenched in every nook. It is the solid foundation of it all. 

Mama is tired. 
Mama is relentless. 
Mama says 🖕🏼.

So… happy belated Mother’s Day! 

#artxmotherhood #artistmother #artistgrants #artmama #happymothersday

“Postpartum Prose”
Opening June 2nd
Arch Enemy Arts
Philadelphia, PA
(And online)

18 new pieces beginning the dialogue of my next creative chapter; inspired by the last six years of life and motherhood.

Where it all began…

In 2016, less than a year after my last solo exhibition (2015) I became pregnant with my first son Lucian. Shortly after his birth I developed deep rooted postpartum anxiety and some postpartum depression. Extreme sleep deprivation, feeding issues, bodily shortcomings, navigating this country’s awful maternity leave and care, attempting to heal myself and my post birth body, and not knowing who I was or who I was becoming made the world go very gray very quickly. 

Just two months prior, my husband and I had bought our first home. We were still learning its loveliness and quirks when Lucian came earthside. Deep into some dark head spaces 3 weeks postpartum (around this EXACT week in 2017), while simultaneously feeling exuberantly in love with and protective over my son, my husband picked a bouquet of roses for me from our new backyard. I, previously, LOATHED flowers. I thought their symbolism for relationships and love to be weak. Everything changed with that gesture. (I still have it… dried and on our mantle next to my wedding flowers which were paper).

That bouquet of backyard flowers (pink and deep fuchsia with rich green leaves) were the ONLY color I had seen in weeks. (That memory is VISCERAL). I hadn’t quite realized the headspace I was in until that moment. 
	
Every late May and early June those roses bloom and I am reminded of those first postpartum weeks. It’s a reflection year after year about this journey. 

This body of work is six years of life experience and a reworking of my entire being. I’m so excited to be “back” and making the most meaningful work (in every way) I never dreamed possible. I’m looking forward to the future but today is the very START of speaking on this journey (visually). 

(Cont in comments)…

“The Care Of This Country”
Oil on canvas
9x12 inches
2023

Now on view at @archenemyarts! Opening tonight 5-9pm and up until July 2nd! #firstfriday #archenemyarts #postpartumprose 

The Care of This Country is a visual representation of my experience navigating the physical, mental, and emotional healthcare system in the US; specifically after developing postpartum anxiety following the birth of my first child.

I unfortunately don’t have the privilege of a mama village close by… but I do have my far away friends who I stay in touch with online. They’ve been so much of what I’ve needed to survive this experience with a sense of community when I need it most. 
Kristine is a joyful acquaintance turned friend turned client turned better friend. She had her beautiful Luciella (nicknamed Luci just like my Lucian is! 😍) in between my boys. We’ve been able to share so many stories, hardships, love, and even clothes back and forth for all the kids. 
She’s a big part of my heart and one of the handful of people I’d move immediately to my neighborhood (a fantasy commune I often conjure of all my favorite women and their families) so we could be the perfect weirdo mamas together. 

Some pieces BELONG to very specific people and I cannot imagine this one going to anyone else now. Big old feeeeeeelings. 😭🥀

“Zusammen”
Oil on canvas 
8” round
2023

I used to write a lot of poetry but that well ran dry about a decade ago. I felt it start coming back very recently and this was the first to fly out of my fingertips. 

Motherhood has shown me my deepest depths and truly unearthed some buried gems I pretended didn’t exist. 

Creating this show has been pure therapy in so many ways. (On view at @archenemyarts until July 2nd. Now online too).

My husband asked me, on the way back from my opening on Friday, if I was worried or concerned that this body of work (and my future plans) would completely disenfranchise my previous collectors. And I’m not…. Because it’s been eight years. What kind of creative would I be if I never grew? I cannot live near worry of unsold pieces from my past collectors. 

It’s also OKAY for people to not like my work as I evolve. You can be drawn to someone’s message in their early 30s and not relate to their life’s stories from their 40s. Art flows. Friendship flows. Collector and artist relationships do too. 

I also know this is stage one of what’s to come. My long term plan is drawn out. I’ve never been someone who moves into trends or try’s to find “the market”. The art and the message is first. Everyone else comes later. I’m not trying to pay my bills this way. This is how I speak. And it’s ok if this chapter isn’t what calls to some right now. There’s a LOT of art to go around. 

But to those who are either here for my whole book or are finding me because of this chapter? WELCOME. I am so overjoyed you’re here. This is the most genuine me I’ve ever been and I’m glad we’re connecting now (or still). It’s bringing along a greater sense of community than I ever imagined.

Oil on canvas
9x12 inches

“With Alex” is a dedication to one of my closest friends this past year and a half (the incomparable @alexgarantart). 

During the nuances of life’s difficulties, having a companion to sit with can be world-changing. While it may be distanced or digital in our current society (especially for those who are sharing in the hardships of early motherhood), the closeness and parallel daily shares can be vital to keeping one’s color.

Alex was pivotal in keeping me afloat once Oscar was born. Her beautiful Maya is just three weeks apart from him. Being able to message her about all things breastfeeding, sleep, and very gross issues at all hours of the night was so much what I needed to get through that stage of life. Being a few weeks apart was a GIFT as baby’s change so rapidly the first year. A 6mo and a 6day old are worlds apart but just three weeks? So much incredible shared and helpful information for our new beings and new bodies. 

I’m so grateful to her and now so joyful she’s in my life daily. 

Cherish your friends, even if they’re all far away. It helps ease the loneliness. 

“With Alex” is currently in view at @archenemyarts in Philadelphia!

This Is Fucking Lonely
Oil on canvas
11x14 inches
2023

Peonies symbolize a range of feelings depending on the culture. For ‘This Is Fucking Lonely’, I pulled from the Greek myth of Paeonia where peonies represent shyness. There are complexities when being an introverted parent. There is a push and pull of thriving in certain isolating situations and simultaneously longing for the brightness of community.

I’ve been battling an ACHE of loneliness since becoming a mother… but very deeply lately. Six years and haven’t found my “group” yet. I hope it’s just a matter of more time. (But my 1.5 year old crawled up in the couch while writing this and said “mama?!” Then gave me a giant unprompted kiss… so I’ll be alright). 

Available at @archenemyarts 
On view until July 2nd!
Direct 🔗 in profile

It’s the last weekend for Postpartum Prose. 

While I have so much more to say (newsletter coming soon)… I want to publicly thank some people. 

First and most importantly… my tiny babes. You are EVERYTHING that rips me open and heals me wholly day in and day out. You’re the most incredible people I’ll ever meet and nothing has inspired me as an artist, and human being, more than you two. “I’m so glad you’re here.”

Second, my incredible husband… for so often seeing and understanding the value that both motherhood, teaching, and my creative work has. It takes a lot to dismantle stereotypes, gender roles, and the weight it all holds (and is ingrained within us) within one generation and you’re doing it beautifully. You honor who I am as a person and that teaches our boys more than I think you’ll ever realize. You are a true partner. I love you. 

Third, to Arch (@archenemyarts) . What the fuck do I even say? Besides Brian and a few friends, you’re the longest relationship I’ve been in and it’s HEALTHY?! No artist could ask more than a space that holds her voice, specifically as it evolves… and ESPECIALLY going from my last body of work to this. You are a home base for me and I’ll never be able to say how much I appreciate you. Lawren @lawrenalice , Noah @noaharchenemy , and now Candice @madame.mustard … the art world needs a million more of you. Philly is the luckiest. 

(Cont in comments)…

What was the last piece of you to fall? Which part of your being held on the longest before you fully transitioned to your next chapter? 
How many petals did you need to let go of before you could welcome change?

“The Last To Fall”

5x7”

Announcement!
I’ve been sitting on this since March 8th, the day after I turned 40… but I don’t believe anything until there’s signed paperwork in front of me. That happened yesterday… so here we are. 

I left my 7th year teaching at @pafacademy an Instructor and will enter my 8th year in September as Assistant Professor. I am really excited to finally have a title that matches what I’ve felt like the last few years… and especially one that matches the effort I’ve been bringing to my classes since year one. 

I am not fully where I want to be with my teaching career. I’m still working toward that… and working through what that will look like these next few years. However, I am trying really hard to celebrate my victories more - learning that the big leaps I so desire require steady steps and not a rocket taking me from A to B (even if this feels like the longest staircase imaginable). 

Me aside… teaching my two main courses year in and out has been one of the greatest joys of my life. I have worked with the most magnificent, talented, energetic, hilarious, kind, and caring humans. This is not, and will never be, a job for me. This is about connection, passing knowledge along, intergenerational camaraderie, guidance, support, and COMMUNITY. 

Grateful. Very very grateful. 
Looking forward to “next” while living in a current state of “proud”. 

Cheers!

First photo by @andyfecile 
Wish I could tag every single one of you from every single class but alas… 10 photos and forgotten usernames (I’m old!)

Thank you all for your creativity and effort. My life has been enriched.

Waited For The Village (It Never Came)
Oil on canvas
9x12 inches
🔴

Still in my feels from Junes show… while I’m preparing for the next few (specifically Octobers, which I can’t wait to talk about). Also starting to research and work through bringing the figure back for a 2024 show lined up. 

There’s momentum right now. I’m acknowledging it’s potential power. It’s thrilling (and scary). 

#botanicalart #archenemyarts #postpartumprose #beautifulbizarre 
#styerspeonies #peony #artxmotherhood #artistmother

Lately Ive been coming to terms with mass popularity not being in the cards for me… at least at my current age and stage of life. Unfortunately, thats how we define REAL artists. Thats how we define success. I have spent the last twenty (plus) years of my life deeply tied to that idea and it’s going to take a while to untangle from it. It is a soundbite in my head that forces me to question my every choice, my voice, and diminishes my smaller (albeit often notable) accomplishments. 

I’m at a very interesting crossroads of life and art right now. One that requires redefinition of self, specifically as a creative. It requires unlearning.

I spent my earlier decades attempting to get at something deeper but not truly succeeding. I had too little life experience. So I worked through ideas and imagery that were… cool. That isn’t to say my work didn’t have meaning but it had “Maria in her 20s” meaning. I had worked out practically nothing until the last few years… I understood little about myself, my life, who I was, my childhood, and the deep impacts all of that had on who I had become as a human. Motherhood forced EVERYTHING to bubble up, be questioned, be unlearned, relearned, dealt with, etc. 

I have no room for cool. I have no room in my being for art as imagery or techniques that are popular. I have no room for slick, trick, or unique simply for the sake of being unique. Theres a part of being a mom that shut all that down… because if I am going to pull time away from my children it has to MEAN SOMETHING not just be for others’ pleasure. And I dont do cool or slick for myself. I am none of that. I truly find it boring. I am not solving anything, beyond easily digestible algorithmic likes, at the easel that way. It doesn’t serve me. 

A lot of food for thought lately. 
Looking forward to my kiddos being back in school to start the newsletter.
Cheers, friends.

Make sure you love the work you make.
Make sure your voice is authentic to your lived experience.
Make work you’re so exceptionally proud of and then make more of it.

Arms Full, a duo exhibition with the incredible @shawnamillerstudio, opens just shy of two weeks from now. 

I am ELATED to be headed to Oslo, Norway with Shawna to see our work converse about tireless love, creativity, mourning, and motherhood. An artist talk will follow to continue this important dialogue. 

It is not lost on me that we are presenting work about motherhood/childhood while so many mothers are without children, and children without mothers, right now as more heartache and violence finds it’s horrific place in our world. But the more I ruminate on the simple act of making, centering this very personal subject matter, the more I grasp at its importance. If a world were to discuss that of love, parenting, childhood, MOTHERS… we’d live a different space mentally, emotionally, physically. I’d like to imagine a world of far more care and understanding. 

Arms Full opens at @femaleartistsoslo on October 26th. An artist discussion to follow on the 27th. Further details to come. 🥀

I took what would normally be a sketchbook practice and turned them into tangible studies to be shared outside my studio. Im so in love with these little pieces but even more so the process… finding the parts of life in my garden forgotten or fleeting, broken bits from reference collection… and giving them a deeper longevity. 

Everything is important. It is the creator who decides what to put on a pedestal. Sometimes that power is lovely and poetic. More often it’s not. So as an artist this is how I wield mine in a world of devastating news cycles and endless violence. I give life back to the passed over. 🥀🖤 

All these studies will be shown at @femaleartistsoslo. Opening on Thursday the 26th. Artist talk with Shawna Miller (@shawnamillerstudio) on Friday the 27th.

“Ships Passing (Our Modern Village)”
oil on linen panel
8x10
🔴

Inspired by those of us in care giving roles (specifically mothers) that want to help one another but cannot pour from an empty cup… ships passing on a stormy night (often sleepless). 

However the meaning changed a bit for me this trip. 

I always felt like I couldn’t give enough to the community I craved (and vise versa) in so many ways, because I lacked the traditional village I needed to keep my cup filled enough for anyone beyond my children. But sitting next to @shawnamillerstudio for a week, conversing with @adiosalasfresas and @silli_von_vanilli and all the incredible women who came out to listen to the genuine stories behind mine and Shawnas work felt like… a different level of caregiving to the community - one I didn’t value before. The artist talk with Shawna felt like TRUE CARE. Conversing and making one another feel SEEN is fucking IMPORTANT. Making visual work to represent this is wildly courageous, political, and encouraging. It felt like giving and receiving simultaneously.

I’m so proud of Shawna and I for doing this show. I’m so proud of us for talking about our work in such meaningful and HONEST ways. I’ve had conversations that will be imprinted on me for life. 

Grateful to @femaleartistsoslo for hosting us and all the incredible humans who made last week an inspiration. 

So much more to say. This trip will take a while to fully formulate. It was a perspective change.

Happy belated Halloween from my crew to you and yours. 

Now I’m ready to put up the Christmas tree because mama needs massive joy after the last two months. I cannot even put into words the inner difficulties of 2023. My entire soul is tired. 

So with that, I’m officially on sabbatical from my non-business Instagram accounts for the rest of November. The noise has been loud and I felt a MASSIVE shift in me/my work post-Norway that I cannot quite grasp on to yet. I’m surrounded by too many voices and outside opinions on life and art. I’ve really started stepping into my own but outside weight is holding me down heavy. 

Im excited to use this time to love on my boys, celebrate TEN YEARS MARRIED to my husband, edit all @irisandecho work, and begin writing again (newsletter/Substack/etc). 

Im working to amplify my voice and I need serious solitude to do so. Im looking forward to it. 

Text or email me if you need me. If you don’t have my personal info, it’s not serious enough. Wait till December. 

With love and intergalactic spots,
Maria

Camomile studies. Oil on linen, mounted to aluminum. 5x7”. Available.

In hindsight, feeling drawn to painting dead and dying flora this Autumn makes so much sense. Oddly not at all FOR the season but because it was exactly what I was going through: the beginnings of a rebirth, unsure of what next season will look like or bring, dark (very very dark), and lonely. 

Art can be such a memory palace. I’m grateful for the ability, even in the worst of hours, to find the quiet to listen to myself… even if I can’t make sense of the voice in the moment.

To post a highlights reel would go against every lesson I was violently thrown into the second half of the year. 

On paper, 2023 was glorious and successful. In practicality, June through December ripped open a self awareness and whirlwind that can only be described as an authentic, what-am-I-truly-here for, intense mid life crisis. 

I have questioned every aspect of my art work in the greater art world. I contemplated (heavily) completely leaving exhibiting. I am making the most deeply personal, art historical, and meaningful work I could conjure at this point of my life and I was (am?!) ready to keep it all active but hanging solely in my home. 

I’m at the very starting point of a decades long plan and I wanted to hide it all… because I have spent the last 15 or so years letting everyone else’s definitions aid in defining most aspects of me… from artist, to teacher, to (less so) mother. 

The last few weeks however… Smoke is clearing. Things are cleansing. I’m redefining. 

A new era is dawning. 
My confidence is grounded and present. 
And she has been so very missed.

A new year won’t create the change I desire. But I will.

-When do we get to call ourselves the “thing” that we feel we are?
-Does imposter syndrome hold us back or is there an unspoken checklist we must go through first?
-Are there arbitrary rules?
-Are titles bestowed on us first?

These are some of the many questions Ive continued asking myself for far too long. And 2023 is when they all caused me to implode. I saw an old friend learn a craft, put their first piece into the world, and immediately offer a workshop. I asked my husband what I was missing because 20 YEARS doing my art and I was petrified I didn’t know enough to do that. His answer? Confidence. 

Ive waited and waited to know MORE… or for those in bigger positions to tell me I was “the thing”. One of those has been “teacher” or “professor”. I see others claim the title almost instantaneously while I waited for the full time title, benefits, and salary of it all. THAT has been a nightmare to navigate… even when doing it all right. So the questions became even further blurred this year when a new title changed nothing and I lost my (even more dedicated) work wife. 

The only conclusion I can come up with is to just do the thing. Call myself the thing. And shut up the voice that keeps telling me I’m not the one to take on the titles. I’ve waited long enough. Learned enough. Have been in the arena for decades. 

So 2024 we’re developing the workshops. 
I’m thrilled. And I hope you’ll come say hi. 
We can do “the thing” together.
